Spatial dyanmics in R, Lab Report 4

Over the past 5.5 weeks you have been learning about single-species population dynamics. This includes density-independent change, density-dependent change, and structured (age or stage classes) change This week concludes the single-species portion of the semester, where we consider single species changing in space. We will be taking two main approaches this week: modeling space implicitly and explicitly. Spatially-implicit models include the effect of space, but do not consider the exact positions (locations, cooridnates) of populaitons. As we will learn in lecture, the Levins and Hanski metapopulation models are spatially-implicit models that include spatial terms like migration and subpopulation extinction. Spatially-explicit models include the effect of space by explicitly considering the positions of populations, with the the dynamics of populations being influenced by one another. In lecture this week and the Lecture Notebook for chapter 5, you will learn about spatially-implicit metapopulation models. For today’s Lab, you will learn about two 1 type of spatially-explicity models: cellular automata (singular, automaton) and mapped lattices. The main difference between these two models is that state variable at each point is binary (presence of absence) with of a single state variabme (the automaton) opposed to continuous with many state variables (the lattice).

1. Cellular atutomata

Cellular automata are perhaps the longest and best-studied spatial model in biology, with origins before efficient computers in the mid-20th century. Cellular automata have several simplifying features, yet display a fantastic diversity of behavior. Here are a few of the features:

  1. Space is discrete. That means that state variables may only occupy pre-defined point locations that are set a priori. Often times space is modeled on a rectangular lattice, which is just another way of saying “a grid.” Grids are not necessarily rectangular, as there are other types, such as hexagonal grids.
  2. The state of a point is discrete and singular. This means that at each one of the points on the grid, there is a single “individual” that can occupy that point. There are variations on this theme, but generally there is only a state.
  3. The “individual” has a neighborhood with which it interacts. This means that there is a pre-set determination of which cells can interact with each other. For the majority of automata there are two neighborhoods: the von Neumann and the Moore neighborhood. The von Neumann neighborhood interacts with the points that that are directly above, to the right, below, and to the left of the focal point (figure below, left). The Moore neighborhood interacts the same as the von Neumann, but it also includes the four adjacent corners (figure below, right).
  4. Initial conditions. The automaton needs to be populated, and the location and number of points that are present (also termed “live”) needs to be determined.
  5. The rules. The rules determine how points (synonymous with cells) interact with one another.
  6. The boundaries. The last feature of automata are the boundaries and how to treat cells that are on the edges of the space.

von Neumann’s The Game of Life

In 1970, mathematician John Conway devised The Game of Life. The game has only four simple rules

  • Live cells with < 2 neighbors die because the local population is too small
  • Live cells with > 3 neighbors die because the local population is too large
  • Live cells survive a time step
  • Empty cells with 3 neighbors are reproduced into

With these rules, the simulations were able to show complex behaviors. Some of the recurrent congigurations include static states, oscillating states (with varying periodicity), and repetitive states that “move” across the grid. Further, the persistence of the siimulation depends on the initial conditions: how many live cells exist and their location relative to one another.

Below I have written a version of The Game of Life. It is not the most computationally efficient (it can be written much faster) nor condensed, but, I hope, it is the most student/human-readable code.

1.2. I would like for you to have an understanding of how this is fomulated. Please translate the code verbally. That is, I would like for you to determine what is happening “under the hood” for the automaton, and summarize. You don’t need to translate the first line (beginning with par()) nor the last 7 lines (beginning with plot()).

  par(mfrow = c(6, 6), mar = c(1, 1, 1, 1))
  rec.rows <- 25
  rec.cols <- 25
  timesteps <- 36

  time.seq <- seq(from = 1, to = timesteps)
  n.frames <- length(time.seq)
  total.time = 10

  # `rbindom()` will return `n` values of `size` samples (coin flips) with some `prob`
  rand.vals <- rbinom(n = rec.rows*rec.cols, size = 1, prob = 0.62)
  ca.mat <- matrix(data = rand.vals, nrow = rec.rows, ncol = rec.cols)
  
  for (times in 1:timesteps){
    for (i in 1:rec.rows) {
      for (j in 1:rec.cols) {
        # Interior rectangle
        if (i != 1 & i != rec.rows & j != 1 & j != rec.cols) {
            N <- ca.mat[i+1, j]
            NE <- ca.mat[i+1, j+1]
            E <- ca.mat[i, j+1]
            SE <- ca.mat[i-1, j+1]
            S <- ca.mat[i-1, j]
            SW <- ca.mat[i-1, j-1]
            W <- ca.mat[i, j-1]
            NW <- ca.mat[i+1, j-1]
        } else {
                # Row 1
            if (i == 1 & j != 1 & i == 1 & j != rec.cols) {
                N <- ca.mat[i+1, j]
                NE <- ca.mat[i+1, j+1]
                E <- ca.mat[i, j+1]
                SE <- ca.mat[rec.rows, j+1]
                S <- ca.mat[rec.rows, j]
                SW <- ca.mat[rec.rows, j-1]
                W <- ca.mat[i, j-1]
                NW <- ca.mat[i+1, j-1]
            }
            # Row rec.rows
                if (i == rec.rows & j != 1 & i == rec.rows & j != rec.cols){
                N <- ca.mat[1, j]
                NE <- ca.mat[1, j+1]
                E <- ca.mat[i, j+1]
                SE <- ca.mat[i-1, j+1]
                S <- ca.mat[i-1, j]
                SW <- ca.mat[i-1, j-1]
                W <- ca.mat[i, j-1]
                NW <- ca.mat[1, j-1]
            }       
            # Col 1
            if (j == 1 & i != 1 & j == 1 & i != rec.rows){
                N <- ca.mat[i+1, j]
                NE <- ca.mat[i+1, j+1]
                E <- ca.mat[i, j+1]
                SE <- ca.mat[i-1, j+1]
                S <- ca.mat[i-1, j]
                SW <- ca.mat[i-1, rec.cols]
                W <- ca.mat[i, rec.cols]
                NW <- ca.mat[i+1, rec.cols]
            }
            # Col rec.cols
            if (j == rec.cols & i != 1 & j == rec.cols & i != rec.rows){
                N <- ca.mat[i+1, j]
                NE <- ca.mat[i+1, 1]
                E <- ca.mat[i, 1]
                SE <- ca.mat[i-1, 1]
                S <- ca.mat[i-1, j]
                SW <- ca.mat[i-1, j-1]
                W <- ca.mat[i, j-1]
                NW <- ca.mat[i+1, j-1]
            }
            # Bottom-left corner
            if (i == 1 & j == 1){
                N <- ca.mat[i+1, j]
                NE <- ca.mat[i+1, j+1]
                E <- ca.mat[i, j+1]
                SE <- ca.mat[rec.rows, j+1]
                S <- ca.mat[rec.rows, j]
                SW <- ca.mat[rec.rows, rec.cols]
                W <- ca.mat[i, rec.cols]
                NW <- ca.mat[i+1, rec.cols]
            }
            # Bottom-right corner
            if (i == 1 & j == rec.cols){
                N <- ca.mat[i+1, j]
                NE <- ca.mat[i+1, 1]
                E <- ca.mat[i, 1]
                SE <- ca.mat[rec.rows, 1]
                S <- ca.mat[rec.rows, j]
                SW <- ca.mat[rec.rows, j-1]
                W <- ca.mat[i, j-1]
                NW <- ca.mat[i+1, j-1]
            }
            # Top-right corner
            if (i == rec.rows & j == rec.cols){
                N <- ca.mat[1, j]
                NE <- ca.mat[1, 1]
                E <- ca.mat[i, 1]
                SE <- ca.mat[i-1, 1]
                S <- ca.mat[i-1, j]
                SW <- ca.mat[i-1, j-1]
                W <- ca.mat[i, j-1]
                NW <- ca.mat[1, j-1]
            }       
            # Top-left corner
            if (i == rec.rows & j == 1){
                N <- ca.mat[1, j]
                NE <- ca.mat[1, 1]
                E <- ca.mat[i, 1]
                SE <- ca.mat[i-1, 1]
                S <- ca.mat[i-1, j]
                SW <- ca.mat[i-1, j-1]
                W <- ca.mat[i, j-1]
                NW <- ca.mat[1, j-1]
            }
        }
        neigbors.sum <- sum(c(N, NE, E, SE, S, SW, W, NW))
  
        if (ca.mat[i, j] == 1) {
            if (neigbors.sum < 2 | neigbors.sum > 3) {
              ca.mat[i, j] <- 0
              } else {
            ca.mat[i, j] <- 1
          }
        } else {
            if (neigbors.sum == 3) ca.mat[i, j] <- 1
        }
      } # end of j loop
    } # end of i loop
      plot(x = 0.5:(rec.cols+1), y = 0.5:(rec.rows+1), main = paste0("Time step = ", times), las = 1, xlab = "Columns", ylab = "Rows", xaxs = "i", yaxs = "i", type = "n", xaxt = "n", yaxt = "n")
      cols.vec <- seq(from = 0.5, to = rec.cols+2, by = 1)
      rows.vec <- seq(from = 0.5, to = rec.rows+2, by = 1)
      segments(x0 = cols.vec, y0 = rep(0, length(cols.vec)), x1 = cols.vec, y1 = rep(rec.rows, length(cols.vec)), lwd = 0.5, col = "grey75")
      segments(y0 = cols.vec, x0 = rep(0, length(rows.vec)), y1 = cols.vec, x1 = rep(rec.cols, length(rows.vec)), lwd = 0.5, col = "grey75")
         image(x = 1:rec.cols, y = 1:rec.rows, t(ca.mat), col = c(NA, "grey40"), add = T, xaxs = "i", yaxs = "i", xaxt = "n", yaxt = "n")
    } # end of times loop
